---
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
import Header from "@/components/Header.astro";
import Footer from "@/components/Footer.astro";

const productSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Service",
  name: "Agentic iOS Consultation",
  provider: {
    "@type": "Person",
    name: "Igor Tarasenko",
    url: "https://tarasenko.dev",
  },
  description:
    "Private consultation and repo teardown for iOS developers and mobile teams adopting Claude Code, Cursor, Xcode agents, and practical AI development workflows.",
  areaServed: "Worldwide",
};
---

<Layout
  title="Agentic iOS Consultation | Igor Tarasenko"
  description="Private consultation and repo teardown for senior iOS developers and mobile teams adopting Claude Code, Cursor, Xcode agents, and practical AI development workflows."
  structuredData={productSchema}
>
  <Header />
  <div class="grid">
    <main id="main-content" class="content prose lab-page">
      <p class="eyebrow">Private consultation · iOS × AI agents</p>
      <h1 class="page-h1">Make your iOS repo usable by agents.</h1>

      <p class="page-lede">
        If Claude Code, Cursor, or Xcode agents feel impressive in demos but
        clumsy inside your real Swift codebase, the problem is rarely just the
        model.
      </p>

      <p>
        Agents need a repo they can understand, commands they can run, feedback
        they can see, and a review loop that catches the dumb stuff before it
        reaches main. Most iOS projects were not built with that loop in mind.
      </p>

      <section class="offer-card">
        <h2>Agentic iOS consultation</h2>
        <p>
          A private working session for senior iOS developers, indie app
          builders, and mobile teams who want practical help making AI coding
          agents useful on a real Swift project.
        </p>
        <div class="facts">
          <span>Private session</span>
          <span>Repo teardown</span>
          <span>Swift / SwiftUI / TCA</span>
          <span>Claude Code / Cursor / Xcode agents</span>
        </div>
        <a
          class="cta cta-primary"
          href="mailto:igor@tarasenko.dev?subject=Agentic%20iOS%20Consultation"
        >
          Send me the problem &rarr;
        </a>
        <a
          class="cta cta-secondary"
          href="mailto:igor@tarasenko.dev?subject=Agentic%20iOS%20Team%20Audit"
        >
          Ask about a team audit &rarr;
        </a>
      </section>

      <h2>Useful if you are trying to</h2>
      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>Set up Claude Code, Cursor, or Xcode agents on a real iOS repo.</li>
        <li>Write project instructions agents will actually follow.</li>
        <li>Make build, test, simulator, and preview commands agent-runnable.</li>
        <li>Find why agents keep making wrong changes in your Swift codebase.</li>
        <li>Design a safer human review loop for AI-generated changes.</li>
        <li>Figure out whether your repo is agent-ready or agent-hostile.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>What I can look at</h2>
      <div class="loop-grid">
        <article>
          <strong>Repo structure</strong>
          <p>Module boundaries, TCA seams, dependency shape, naming, and how much context an agent has to infer.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
          <strong>Agent context</strong>
          <p><code>CLAUDE.md</code>, <code>AGENTS.md</code>, examples, conventions, constraints, and failure rules.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
          <strong>Feedback loop</strong>
          <p>Build, test, simulator, SwiftUI previews, screenshots, and how quickly bad work becomes visible.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
          <strong>Verification</strong>
          <p>Tests, snapshots, deterministic checks, review prompts, and rollback paths.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
          <strong>Shipping workflow</strong>
          <p>How an AI-assisted change moves from idea to branch to review to App Store-safe release.</p>
        </article>
      </div>

      <h2>Possible session shapes</h2>
      <div class="schedule">
        <div>
          <h3>One-off consultation</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>You send the repo or describe the failure mode.</li>
            <li>We identify the bottleneck.</li>
            <li>You leave with a concrete next move, not a lecture.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3>Repo teardown</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>I review the agent-readiness of the codebase.</li>
            <li>You get findings, risks, and suggested changes.</li>
            <li>Good fit before a team rollout or deeper sprint.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3>Team audit</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>For mobile teams testing agentic development.</li>
            <li>Focus on workflow, safety, code review, and adoption.</li>
            <li>Useful before standardizing tools across a team.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3>Small lab, if there is demand</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>If several senior iOS devs want the same help.</li>
            <li>Small group, hands-on, no course platform cosplay.</li>
            <li>Built from real problems people bring in.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>Why me</h2>
      <p>
        I&rsquo;m Igor Tarasenko, ex-Uber, lead iOS engineer in Amsterdam. I built
        WhisperBoard, an on-device transcription app with 50k+ downloads,
        a 4.8 App Store rating, and 1,035 GitHub stars. I&rsquo;ve been running
        agent-driven iOS workflows before Xcode shipped native agent support.
      </p>
      <p>
        I built preview tooling because the feedback loop was the bottleneck.
        That is the point here: make agents useful by giving them a repo they
        can understand, commands they can run, and evidence they can check.
      </p>

      <section class="offer-card compact">
        <h2>Send me the messy version</h2>
        <p>
          You do not need a polished brief. Send the repo shape, the tool you are
          trying, what keeps failing, and what you want the agent to handle.
          I&rsquo;ll tell you whether I can help and what the smallest useful session
          should be.
        </p>
        <a
          class="cta cta-primary"
          href="mailto:igor@tarasenko.dev?subject=Agentic%20iOS%20Consultation"
        >
          Email Igor &rarr;
        </a>
      </section>

      <Footer />
    </main>
  </div>
</Layout>

<style>
  .lab-page {
    max-width: 820px;
  }

  .eyebrow {
    color: var(--accent);
    font-family: var(--font-mono-stack);
    font-size: 13px;
    margin-bottom: 16px;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
  }

  .offer-card {
    border: 1px solid var(--rule);
    padding: 28px;
    margin: 40px 0;
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent) 5%, transparent);
  }

  .offer-card h2 {
    margin-top: 0;
  }

  .facts {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 8px;
    margin: 24px 0;
  }

  .facts span {
    border: 1px solid var(--rule);
    padding: 6px 10px;
    font-family: var(--font-mono-stack);
    font-size: 13px;
  }

  .cta {
    display: inline-block;
    margin: 8px 12px 0 0;
    padding: 14px 18px;
    border: 1px solid var(--ink);
    font-weight: 650;
  }

  .cta-primary {
    background: var(--ink);
    color: var(--bg);
  }

  .cta-primary:hover {
    color: var(--bg);
    background: var(--accent);
    border-color: var(--accent);
  }

  .cta-secondary {
    border-color: var(--rule);
  }

  .check-list li::marker {
    color: var(--accent);
  }

  .loop-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: 16px;
    margin: 28px 0;
  }

  .loop-grid article,
  .schedule > div {
    border: 1px solid var(--rule);
    padding: 18px;
  }

  .loop-grid p {
    margin: 8px 0 0;
    color: var(--muted);
  }

  .schedule {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: 16px;
    margin: 24px 0;
  }

  .schedule h3 {
    font-size: 18px;
    margin-bottom: 8px;
  }

  .compact {
    margin-top: 56px;
  }

  @media (max-width: 720px) {
    .loop-grid,
    .schedule {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
